Introduction#

This chapter will be relatively dataframe-agnostic, but we will use Polars dataframe as a comparion for learning how to do data visualization using grammar of graphics popularized by Leland Wilkinson.

“Data Visualization needs a Language”: Grammar of Graphics#

Over time, certain technologies have emerged as “killer apps” that propelled once-niche programming languages into widespread popularity.

Ruby gained mainstream traction thanks to Ruby on Rails, the web development framework that enabled rapid application development. JavaScript became ubiquitous largely due to NodeJS and front/full-stack frameworks that provided structure for complex web applications.

Python’s ascendance is closely tied to its extensive data science libraries like NumPy, Pandas, and scikit-learn, which enabled Python to become the standard for data analysis and machine learning, during the rapidly developing data industry.

While originally developed as a statistical programming language, R gained significant traction in data visualization thanks to ggplot2, an elegant and versatile plotting library based on the “grammar of graphics” theory. ggplot2 enabled R users to create publication-quality graphics with concise code.

Overview of Data Visualization libraries#

  • Python:

    • Matplotlib

    • Seaborn

    • Plotly

    • Bokeh

    • Altair

  • Business Intelligence tools:

Add another line temp_min#

raw_df = pl.from_pandas(data.seattle_weather())

plot_df = raw_df

fig_temp_max = (
    alt.Chart(plot_df).mark_line(color="lightblue").encode(
        x="date",
        y="temp_max"
    )
)

fig_temp_min = (
    alt.Chart(plot_df).mark_line(color="darkred").encode(
        x="date",
        y="temp_min"
    )
)

(fig_temp_max + fig_temp_min).properties(width=800)

It’s starting to get a bit verbose and the lines aren’t cutting it

Bar Chart#

Bar chart is used everywhere. As much as sometimes there are ill-advised efforts to use bar chart where lines suffice, even when used incorrectly, it’s hard to mess it up.

Seattle Weather: Average Precipitation#

When looking at the daily precipitation records, you may wonder how to display this.

import altair as alt
import polars as pl
from vega_datasets import data

raw_df = pl.from_pandas(data.seattle_weather())

plot_df = raw_df    # For future manipulation step

fig = alt.Chart(plot_df).mark_line().encode(
    x="date",
    y="temp_max"
)
fig

Whenever you see this type of “death by data dots”, it means you should aggregate it or find another dimension to separate the dots.

One of more straight forward steps is to calculate min, max, average, median for a given time frame.

Let’s do this in Polars

Basic aesthetics#

import altair as alt
import polars as pl
from vega_datasets import data

plot_df = pl.from_pandas(data.seattle_weather())

fig = alt.Chart(plot_df).mark_line().encode(
    x=alt.X("date").title("Date"),
    y=alt.Y("temp_max").title("Max Temperature (deg Celsius)")
)
fig.properties(
    title=alt.Title(
        "Daily Max Temperatures in Seattle (2012-2015)",
        fontSize=20,
    ),
    width=800,
    height=200
)

        y=alt.Y("temp_max").title("Max Temperature (deg Celsius)"),
        color=alt.Color("wind").scale(scheme="purpleorange"),
        size=alt.Size("wind").scale(domain=[0, 30]),
        tooltip=alt.Tooltip([
            "date",
            "wind",

alt.Chart(
    plot_df.with_columns(
        week_start = (
            pl.when(
                pl.col("date").dt.weekday() == 1
            )
            .then(pl.col("date"))
            .otherwise(None)
            .forward_fill()
        )
    )
    .group_by("week_start").agg(
        mean_wind = pl.col("wind").mean()
    )
).encode(
    x="week_start", 
    y="mean_wind"
).mark_bar()

alt.Chart(
    plot_df.with_columns(
        week_of_year = pl.col("date").dt.week()
    )
    .group_by("week_of_year").agg(
        mean_wind = pl.col("wind").mean()
    )
).encode(
    x="week_of_year", 
    y="mean_wind"
).mark_bar()

monthly_mean_wind_df = (
    plot_df
    .group_by(pl.col("date").dt.month().alias("month_of_year"))
    .agg(mean_wind = pl.col("wind").mean())
    .sort("month_of_year")
)

Concatenated Charts#

base = alt.Chart(plot_df)

selection = alt.selection_point(encodings=["x"])

bar_fig = (
    base.mark_bar().encode(
        x="month(date)",
        y="mean(wind)",
        color=alt.condition(
            selection,
            alt.Color("mean(temp_max):Q"),
            alt.value("lightgray")
        ),
    )
)
quarter_fig = (
    base.mark_circle().encode(
        x="temp_max",
        y="wind",
        color=alt.condition(
            selection,
            alt.Color("quarter(date):N"),
            alt.value("lightgray")
        ),
        opacity=alt.value(0.5)
    )
)

(
    (quarter_fig | bar_fig)
    .add_params(selection)
    .resolve_scale(color="independent")
)

bar_fig
